The principle of the real contracta is part performance: their causa civilis was the fact that one of the parties had done all tbat be had primarily undertaken. shortly after the fall of the Republic, and per· haps, as has been supposed, through the influence of the jurist labeo (Dig. 15. 5. ι. ι; ib. ro pr. 3 ib. ao pn), the Roman contract system received a considerable extension by a more general recognition of tbis principle. Every agreement, even though not belonging to any of the three hitherto established classes of contract, in which an act on the one side was the consideration for an act on the other, was at length, though only by a gradual development, held enforceable by action at tbe suit of that party who had performed all to which he was bound under its terms: ‘sed et si in alium contractum res non transeat, subsit tamen causa, ele· ganter Aristo Celso respondit, esse obligationem, ut puta dedi tibi rem, ut mihi aliam dares, dedi, ut aliquid facias, boc συνάλλαγμα esse, et hinc nasci civilem obligationem’ Dig. 2. 14. 17. 2. The essentia! marks of sucb actionable agreement thus are (1) mutualiry; there must bea συνάλλαγμα, e. g. an act must be promised on the one side in return for an act ou the other; (2) there must have been performance on one side; tbe mere bilateral agreement gives rise to no civil obligation: ‘item emptio ac venditio nuda consentientium voluntate contrahitur, permutatio autem ex re tradita initium obligationi praebet, alioquin, si res nondum tradita sit, nudo consensu constitui obligationem dicemus, quod in bis duntaxat receptum est, quae nomen suum habent, ut in emptione, venditione, conductione, mandato’ Dig. ro 4 1. 2.

Such agreements are by the modern civilians called innominate (real) contracts ; the Romans themselves do not call them ‘contractus' and in fact have no general designation for them. Tbough they are roughly classified by Paulus according to the possible acts which might be tbe respective considerations for one another (‘aut enim do tibi ut des, aut do ut facias, aut facio ut des, aut facio ut facias’ Dig. 19. 5. 5. pn), the more usual clue to their existence is the mention of the action by whicb they were pursued, the actio civilis in factum or praescriptis verbis (Tit. 24. r and 2 infe), by which the party who had performed could exact counter performance or recover damages from the other ; against him uo action lay until such counter performance had ensued, so that, if that other refused to keep his promise, and his own part of the agreement bad consisted in a ‘dare,' he could redemand what he had conveyed by the older remedy known as condictio causa data causa non secuta; or be was free to change his mind, and sue for reconveyance‚ as it is said, ‘ex mera poenitentia: ' ‘sed si tibi dedero, ut Stichum manumittas, si uon
